abstract: TACOMA, Washington, Nov. 30. -- F. X. Beaudet of this place has brought from the Klondike evidence that prehistoric man used solid-silver nails in his shoes. abstract: ALTOONA, Penn., Dec. 1 -- Shortly after 2 o'clock this morning Mrs. Mary C. abstract: GOSHEN, N.Y., Dec. 1 -- The Rev. George C. Betts, rector of St. James's Episcopal Church, died suddenly last night. He fell ill with heart disease a year ago, but the attack had passed away and he was apparently in excellent health late yesterday. He remained until 10:45 o'clock in his study and then went into the bathroom to shave himself, so that he would be ready for an early service.

abstract: BALTIMORE, Dec. 2. -- The market today was again dull and backward, the demand showing decided reluctance when it was learned that gold had been engaged for export to Euripe, Prices held rather steady because the local level is believed to be already as low as it ought to go. abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 2. -- The Secretary of the Treasury to-day transmitted to Congress the estimates of appropriations required for the Government service for the fiscal year ending June 30, 1903, as furnished by the heads of the several executive departments. abstract: MOUNT HOLLY, N.J., Dec. 3. -- Charles Brown, one of the murderers of Washington Hunter, paid the penalty of his share of the crime in the jail yard this morning. A short time before he died he made a desperate attempt to escape. In doing so he wounded a constable, but not seriously. He succeeded only in getting into the jail yard, where he was cowed into surrender.

abstract: BALTIMORE, Dec. 4. -- The local market was quiet to-day so far as the volume of trading counted, but it was better in tone and generally higher in prices. The somewhat more favorable conditions in Wall Street had a very perceptible influence here. The pressure on United Railways relaxed sufficently, or rather the buying, of the issues improved sufficiently, to make possible a fractional net gain.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 4. -- Practically the entire session of the Senate to-day was devoted to the introduction of bills and resolutions. abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Dec. 5. -- The Philadelphia market was very dull to-day. A wavering course in the afternoon wiped out most of the grains of a strong tone in the morning, leaving the list at the close at about where It stood last night. There was a steady demand for Union Traction and for a while this braced the list, but when the Readings began to fall off the general tone became weaker.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 6 -- Exportation of manufactures from the United States continues to show a healthy growth in nearly all important articles except copper and iron and steel. The export figures just made public by the Treasury Bureau of Statistics show that in the ten months ending with October exports of copper have fallen about $23,000,000 and exports of iron and steel about $23,000,000, making a total reduction in these two classes of $40,445,685.

abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: I would like to answer Dr. B. S. Talmey. abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 11 -- The Democratic Senators to-day held their first caucus of the present session. abstract: HARTFORD, Conn., Dec. 14. -- The Young Men's Christian Association basket ball team surprised a big crowd to-night by defeating the strong Yale team by a score of 18 to 15 in a game that was fast and exciting all through. abstract: PORT JERVIS, N.Y., Dec. 15. -- Not since the memorable ice gorge of 1875 has there been such a freshet in the Delaware and Neverslnk. Rivers through this section as there was last night. abstract: PERCY, Ill., Dec. 15. -- Kaskaskia, the first capital of Illinois, will soon be wiped out of official existence by an order of the Postmaster General, effective on Jan. 1, 1902. Only five families now live in the once flourishing town, and the department has decided to abolish the Post Office and accommodate the residents through the extension of a rural free delivery route from Fort Gage.

abstract: PORTLAND. Me., Dec. 16. -- This State to-night is suffering from one of the most severe storms in its history, hourly reports telling of disaster that adds thousands of dollars to the aggregate damage. The three principal rivers and innumerable smaller streams have overflowed their banks, submerging vast areas, washing away bridges, buildings, and great quantities of logs and lumber and flooding factories, mills, and dwellings.

abstract: LONDON, Dec. 17 -- Money was firm and in active demand to-day. Supplies were inconsiderable, though rather more plentiful than yesterday. No abundance is expected before the New Year, unless the Government disbuses freely. Discounts were depressed by the hardening of foreign exchanges, the small supply of bills, and the continued inquiry from the Continent.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Dec. 17 -- Harriet P. Murphy, prominent in church and society circles and Treasurer of the Kingsley House Fund, was murdered at her home, 6,221 Howe Street, in the East End, by a burglar about 3 o'clock this morning. abstract: SPRINGFIELD, Ohio, Dec. 21. -- Ohio, particularly Central Ohio, is now experiencing the worst coal famine ever known here. abstract: MONTCLAIR, N.J., Dec. 21. -- The Bible Teachers' College located here will be removed to New York after the holidays. The headquarters for the Winter will be in Broadway Tabernacle, and a permanent place will be found near Herald Square. abstract: Stage animals are very proud of the organs they can move. abstract: BERLIN, Dec. 22 -- The Boerse has already begun to assume its holiday aspect, dealers being inclined to close their engagements before the holidays. The volume of business during the past week, excepting transactions in Government funds, was extremely light. The public shows a strong disinclination for all speculative securities, but an increased appetite, however, for fixed interest bearers, in which during the week there were large transactions.

abstract: ALBANY, N.Y., Dec. 22 -- State Labor Commissioner John McMackin says in his quarterly bulletin that during the third quarter of the year 1899 only 2.3 per cent, of the trades unionists were continuously idle, last year 3.4 per cent., and this year 3.1 per cent. abstract: BALTIMORE, Dec. 22 -- "Willie" Keeler, the clever baseball player, has three engagements open to him. Manager Hanlon of the Brooklyns realizes that "Joe" Kelley will more than likely play with Baltimore next season, and for this reason he is anxious to keep Keeler. Hanlon says that Dwyer of the Detroit Club has offered Keeler $3,000, but that the Brooklyn owners are prepared to make an effort to keep the little fielder.

abstract: When we last spoke of the retirement of Secretary GAGE he had not only given no intimation that it was about to occur, but he had denied the reports made from time to time to that effect. abstract: LONDON, Dec. 22 -- The stock market generally was more cheerful during the last week, chiefly owing to the growing belief here and on the Continent that the war in South Africa is really winding up at last. Speculators drew additional encouragement from the better outlook in the United States, the revival of confidence in France, and the belief that the worst of the German crisis is past.

abstract: NEW ORLEANS, Dec. 22 -- Because he had played the races and lost, a man who gave his name as Walter F. Leighton, Jr., of New York, tried to commit suicide yesterday evening. He jumped from the ferryboat Nathalie Hamilton when the boat was in midstream. Had it not been for the prompt work of the Captain in reversing the engines and lowering a lifeboat he would have succeeded in his purpose.

abstract: LONDON, Dec. 24 -- The British Government is watching with considerable anxiety the progress of the dispute between the Chilean and Argentine Republics. It was stated at a late hour yesterday that neither side had yet approached the British Foreign Office. If both Chile and Argentina request Great Britain to arbitrate the matters in dispute, Lord Lansdowne, the Foreign Secretary, will promptly acquiesce.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Dec. 23 -- Mrs. Roosevelt gave a tea this afternoon in honor of her sister, Miss Carew, who is visiting at the White House. Three hundred invited guests were present. abstract: Disheartened and melancholy because she was away from her home in Kingston on Christmas Day, Annie Davenport, a pretty eighteen-year-old girl, attempted to end her life in her apartments at 331 East One Hundred and Twenty-second Street last night by drinking carbolic acid. Only two months ago she was at school in Kingston, where her people are well to do.

abstract: KEYPORT, N.J., Dec. 20 -- The families of Patrick Kearney and Peter Lewis of this place spent a sad Christmas Day yesterday. They received word early yesterday morning that both men had been drowned off Rockaway Beach by the capsizing of a small sailboat. Kearney and Lewis were oystermen, and left Keyport for several days at a time to work in the oyster beds at Rockaway.

abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Dec. 26 -- The Yale basket ball team left this afternoon for the longest Western trip a Yale team has ever taken. abstract: WILLEMSTED, Island of Curacao, Dec. 28 -- Reports received here to-day from Caracas are to the effect that the relations between Germany and Venezuela become more strained every day. abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: In to-day's TIMES I read an account of the usual accident which is of almost daily occurrence, and to which no one seems to object.
